  "final_answer": "One clear comparison is an income band around \\textbf{2.55–3.03} in median income:\n\n- \\textbf{INLAND}: median income about 2.75, median house value about 98,100\n- \\textbf{ISLAND}: median income about 2.83, median house value about 414,700\n\nThat is a house-value gap of roughly \\textbf{316,600}, despite very similar income levels.\n\nThe most likely explanation is location rather than income: coastal or island proximity tends to command a large premium because of scenery, limited land supply, and higher desirability. The island area also has older housing stock (median age 52 vs. 24), which may indicate a more established or historically desirable market. Broader neighborhood factors—such as access to water, amenities, and scarcity of housing—likely explain much of the difference as well.",
